and it's unfavorable,

15:19.371 --> 15:20.971
we'll look like we're scrambling.

15:21.006 --> 15:23.473
Before a verdict, we can
better position ourselves.

15:23.509 --> 15:25.843
Fine. So call Bob Drag

15:25.878 --> 15:28.579
and tell him we have
a world-class attorney

15:28.614 --> 15:32.115
who apparently never learned
"I before E except after C,"

15:32.151 --> 15:34.151
and tell him that, one way or another,

15:34.186 --> 15:35.953
we will emerge victorious.

15:35.988 --> 15:38.021
I say that we do one better

15:38.057 --> 15:39.590
and we go to New York

15:39.625 --> 15:42.292
and we tell him that in person.

15:42.328 --> 15:45.262
But we... we're in
the middle of a trial.

15:45.297 --> 15:48.665
And besides, the publisher
is your purview.

15:48.701 --> 15:50.212
Yes, but we'll make a much better case

15:50.236 --> 15:52.469
that Masters & Johnson are back on track

15:52.504 --> 15:55.806
if both Masters and Johnson
are in that room.

15:55.841 --> 15:58.108
Together.

15:58.143 --> 16:01.712
I've already asked Betty
to book the first flight.

16:04.049 --> 16:07.184
You just... assumed I'd go?

16:08.754 --> 16:10.721
I... hoped.

16:15.194 --> 16:17.794
There... there's no way. I
have to review this statement,

16:17.830 --> 16:19.830
and, uh, I'm working
on a list of questions

16:19.865 --> 16:21.732
for the prosecution's witnesses.

16:21.767 --> 16:23.812
You really don't think that
Keller's got that covered?

16:23.836 --> 16:25.502
What if he doesn't?

16:25.537 --> 16:28.538
You know, he may have dazzled
you with his Supreme Court talk,

16:28.574 --> 16:31.808
but... you know,
appeal could take years.

16:31.844 --> 16:34.811
This has been hanging
over my head long enough.

16:34.847 --> 16:36.546
A win would mean a fresh start.

16:36.582 --> 16:38.348
Fresh start? That's what you want?

16:38.384 --> 16:40.584
- Mm-hm. - Seems to
me that you've been

16:40.619 --> 16:43.086
backsliding, more than anything.

16:45.291 --> 16:48.592
The other morning when I
dropped off Libby's coat,

16:48.627 --> 16:52.763
it seemed that you and she... You two...

16:52.798 --> 16:54.865
Libby and I are considering reconciling.

16:58.037 --> 17:01.238
Well, that's... curious.

17:02.808 --> 17:05.675
Can I ask why? What's changed?

17:05.711 --> 17:08.578
Why would things be different
between the two of you now?

17:08.614 --> 17:11.580
Well, we're gonna work
to make things different.

17:11.617 --> 17:13.349
Do you remember what you said to me

17:13.385 --> 17:17.721
when I was considering getting
back together with George?

17:17.756 --> 17:22.459
You asked me why I would want
to make the same mistake twice.

17:23.796 --> 17:25.796
And you were right.

17:27.598 --> 17:29.066
There was nothing between us

17:29.101 --> 17:33.670
but a familiar old pattern.

17:35.674 --> 17:39.242
Trust me, Bill.
Falling into old patterns...

17:39.278 --> 17:42.112
can be dangerous.

17:42.147 --> 17:43.780
Dangerous.

17:45.284 --> 17:47.017
You want a fresh start?

17:50.022 --> 17:51.655
Then come to New York.

17:54.660 --> 17:57.394
We can... both reinvest

17:57.429 --> 18:01.598
in what has always given
us the most satisfaction...

18:03.769 --> 18:05.602
The work.

18:11.477 --> 18:13.844
I'm gonna put my focus
where it belongs, on...

18:13.879 --> 18:15.412
On the court case.

18:15.447 --> 18:16.947
But I think you're right.

18:16.982 --> 18:21.151
You... you should focus on
reviving interest in the book.

18:21.186 --> 18:24.354
And I'm sure you'll be
up to that task without me.

18:51.917 --> 18:54.818
I don't need prepping,
because I'm not testifying.

18:54.853 --> 18:56.787
And I'm not so stupid
that I would reveal

18:56.822 --> 18:58.488
Bill's and my situation.

18:58.524 --> 18:59.873
He's the father of my children.

18:59.977 --> 19:01.503
I don't want him to end up in jail.

19:01.527 --> 19:03.293
All right. But the press will accost you

19:03.328 --> 19:05.529
on the courthouse steps,
try to get you to say things.

19:05.564 --> 19:07.397
You can't hide from the cameras.

19:07.433 --> 19:10.000
They'd rather catch you running
away than standing still.

19:10.035 --> 19:12.335
I have no intention of
running, Mr. Keller.

19:12.371 --> 19:13.804
I seem to remember a party

19:13.839 --> 19:16.073
where I was left holding a plaid cape.

19:16.108 --> 19:17.340
Are we through, then?

19:17.376 --> 19:19.743
Not quite.

19:19.778 --> 19:24.014
So, some reporter focuses a
camera on your gorgeous face:

19:24.049 --> 19:26.716
"Mrs. Masters, your husband is charged

19:26.752 --> 19:29.886
with pandering and prostitution."

19:29.922 --> 19:31.421
What do you say?

19:31.457 --> 19:35.525
This case was trumped up
by an overzealous prosecution

19:35.561 --> 19:38.862
bent on destroying my husband's
years of scientific work.

19:38.897 --> 19:41.364
I am very proud of what
my husband has accomplished

19:41.400 --> 19:43.867
and of his contributions to science.

19:43.902 --> 19:45.202
- Oh, my goodness.
- You know,

19:45.237 --> 19:46.614
I'm beginning to believe
this whole thing

19:46.638 --> 19:48.516
was just an excuse to make
me sit down with you.

19:48.540 --> 19:50.718
And my fancy footwork in the
courtroom didn't impress you?

19:50.742 --> 19:53.376
- I could see you watching me.
- We are done here.

19:53.412 --> 19:55.390
How about a drink? Come on.
It's five o'clock somewhere.

19:55.414 --> 19:58.381
I know a great little jazz club
just a couple blocks away.

19:58.417 --> 19:59.816
What do you say?

20:02.621 --> 20:04.955
I'm very proud of my husband's
accomplishments

20:04.990 --> 20:06.923
and his contribution to science.

20:10.129 --> 20:11.795
He's definitely the spy. He's the one

20:11.830 --> 20:13.763
that took the photo of us
and showed it to Bill.

20:13.799 --> 20:15.210
Yeah, but not before
he showed it to you,

20:15.234 --> 20:16.766
which means he's not a snitch.

20:16.802 --> 20:19.302
Well, we'll see what he says
when we confront him.

20:19.338 --> 20:20.815
Reproductive Biology
Research Foundation.

20:20.839 --> 20:22.072
Lester?

20:22.107 --> 20:23.573
Yes, and who am I speaking with?

20:23.609 --> 20:24.819
Okay, he's not here. Let's come back.

20:24.843 --> 20:26.109
Lester?

20:30.983 --> 20:32.082
Look at this.

20:34.286 --> 20:36.753
No, I'm sorry. The whole
morning is completely full.

20:36.788 --> 20:38.622
But I can give you a noon appointment.

20:38.657 --> 20:41.424
That's the earliest that I have.

20:41.460 --> 20:42.637
Or we could try for the next day.

20:42.661 --> 20:45.228
I have a, uh, 2:30.

20:45.264 --> 20:46.830
They've got the whole place wired.

20:46.865 --> 20:50.267
Labeled and
organized by room, date, time.

20:50.302 --> 20:52.435
Why? If they were taping us to train us,

20:52.471 --> 20:54.070
wouldn't they tell us?

20:54.106 --> 20:55.650
It's like they want
to catch us at something.

20:55.674 --> 20:57.841
You might expect this
if there'd been complaints

20:57.876 --> 21:01.178
or if we'd been
foisted upon her by a superior.

21:01.213 --> 21:03.079
You think Virginia is behind this?

21:03.115 --> 21:06.516
God, to think how many offers I had...

21:06.552 --> 21:09.286
Boston Lying-In, UCLA,
Columbia Presbyterian.

21:09.321 --> 21:11.121
I gave them all up to be treated

21:11.156 --> 21:13.456
like an untrustworthy
incompetent by a woman

21:13.492 --> 21:14.991
- who isn't even a doctor!
- Shh, shh.

21:16.962 --> 21:18.662
We cannot stay here, Art.

21:18.697 --> 21:20.041
How will it look to a potential employer

21:20.065 --> 21:21.765
if we jump ship not even two months in?

21:21.800 --> 21:23.500
I don't care how it looks.

21:23.535 --> 21:25.302
I'm surprised that you do.

21:25.337 --> 21:26.948
Or maybe I'm not. You spent
the night together.

21:26.972 --> 21:28.972
She's worked her many charms on you.

21:29.007 --> 21:33.009
Look. I'm just trying to imagine
things from their point of view.

21:33.045 --> 21:35.156
I think they're letting us in
on a process that, until now,

21:35.180 --> 21:36.980
has only involved the two of them...

21:37.015 --> 21:39.216
That's gotta be difficult.

21:41.520 --> 21:43.486
If it doesn't get better, we leave.

21:44.890 --> 21:46.089
Okay.

21:51.830 --> 21:53.230
Mr. Drag?

21:54.366 --> 21:55.732
How was your flight?

21:55.767 --> 21:57.968
Uneventful. There was some turbulence...

21:58.003 --> 21:59.069
I wasn't really asking.

21:59.104 --> 22:00.415
I was being what we call "polite."

22:00.439 --> 22:01.638
It's a concept that may be

22:01.673 --> 22:03.373
somewhat foreign to you, Mrs. Johnson.

22:03.408 --> 22:05.048
You see, showing up at
my office like this

22:05.077 --> 22:07.877
after I made it
absolutely clear to your secretary

22:07.913 --> 22:09.646
that I wasn't available this afternoon

22:09.681 --> 22:11.815
would be what we call "impolite."

22:11.850 --> 22:13.516
I understand.

22:13.552 --> 22:16.353
Though I worried that it
would be more impolite

22:16.388 --> 22:18.032
to not at least stop by
and say hello when I was

22:18.056 --> 22:20.323
just around the corner
meeting with Simon & Schuster.

22:20.359 --> 22:22.726
They're so excited about
Human Sexual Inadequacy.

22:22.761 --> 22:24.861
The keep saying it's
gonna be another best-seller.

22:24.896 --> 22:27.397
Did you meet with Mr.
Simon or Mr. Schuster?

22:27.432 --> 22:30.567
Bob Simon has been dead for ten years,

22:30.602 --> 22:32.669
but nice try.

22:32.704 --> 22:36.239
The point is Bill and I
are very loyal to you,

22:36.275 --> 22:38.875
especially after everything
we put you through in St. Louis.

22:38.910 --> 22:41.778
Don't. The two of you
have been nothing but trouble,

22:41.813 --> 22:44.347
and the last thing I need is trouble.

22:44.383 --> 22:45.882
Did you change offices?

22:45.917 --> 22:47.550
Didn't your office used to be upstairs?

22:47.586 --> 22:49.731
Excuse me, please. I'm
gonna be late for a launch party.

22:49.755 --> 22:52.122
Oh, well, why don't we
meet up after the party?

22:52.157 --> 22:54.724
I haven't even begun to tell you
about the new work we're doing:

22:54.760 --> 22:56.359
fetishes, deviance.

22:56.395 --> 22:58.094
We treated a man a couple of weeks ago

22:58.130 --> 23:00.463
with a predilection
for his wife's high heels.

23:00.499 --> 23:02.132
- Wearing them?
- Copulating with them.

23:02.167 --> 23:06.369
He'll make a compelling
case study for the new book.

23:06.405 --> 23:08.238
What?

23:08.273 --> 23:09.773
Too bad you're wearing that.

23:09.808 --> 23:13.276
I'd take you to the party,
but it's black tie.

23:13.312 --> 23:15.912
Isn't Saks just around the corner?

23:17.082 --> 23:18.982
How'd it go?

23:19.017 --> 23:22.719
Well, I think they're
all down for the count.

23:22.754 --> 23:26.656
And Johnny snores now,
which is kind of odd.

23:30.996 --> 23:32.495
Uh... what are you doing?

23:32.531 --> 23:33.741
A woman in my group gives them away

23:33.765 --> 23:35.732
in exchange for frozen casseroles.

23:35.767 --> 23:36.900
She hates to cook.

23:36.935 --> 23:38.068
Want some?

23:38.103 --> 23:40.003
No.

23:40.038 --> 23:42.038
I'll take a drink, though,
if you're pouring.

23:44.109 --> 23:45.475
I noticed on Saturday

23:45.510 --> 23:46.943
that the back porch light was out.

23:46.978 --> 23:48.144
I thought I'd fix it.

23:48.180 --> 23:49.279
Fixed it myself.

23:51.350 --> 23:52.816
You found the right screwdriver?

23:52.851 --> 23:54.918
I'm not helpless, Bill.

23:54.953 --> 23:56.186
Uh...

23:56.221 --> 23:57.687
what about the disposal?

23:57.723 --> 23:59.189
It's fine.

24:00.392 --> 24:01.858
Bill, if there's anything broken,

24:01.893 --> 24:03.393
I will let you know.

24:06.498 --> 24:07.997
- Thank you.
- Mm-hmm.

24:11.737 --> 24:14.371
How about us?

24:14.406 --> 24:18.007
Can I fix us?

24:18.043 --> 24:21.378
Those, uh, three wishes of
yours were a good start.

24:21.413 --> 24:23.847
Don't you think?

24:23.882 --> 24:26.116
Maybe you could

24:26.151 --> 24:28.385
think of a few more items
to add to the list,

24:28.420 --> 24:32.021
and I could check them off one by one.

24:32.057 --> 24:33.056
Hmm.

24:33.091 --> 24:34.691
Seemed to work the other night.

24:34.726 --> 24:36.459
I think the other night is proof

24:36.495 --> 24:40.196
that neither of us quite knows
how a separation works.

24:40.232 --> 24:41.965
Is that a bad thing?

24:42.000 --> 24:43.967
I guess not.

24:44.002 --> 24:46.770
We're just in uncharted waters.

24:51.042 --> 24:55.044
- So, these, um...
- these uncharted waters...

24:57.349 --> 24:59.749
Is there any chance of

24:59.785 --> 25:02.018
what happened the
other night happening again?

25:04.556 --> 25:06.489
Or...

25:06.525 --> 25:11.494
we could experiment a little.

25:11.530 --> 25:13.830
What we did the other night...
I gather that there's a way

25:13.865 --> 25:17.934
that we can do it to each other

25:17.969 --> 25:19.335
at the same time.

25:19.371 --> 25:21.604
I believe there's even

25:21.640 --> 25:24.174
a number for it.

25:30.415 --> 25:34.250
I cannot apologize enough
for what happened in St. Louis.

25:34.286 --> 25:36.119
The way Bill and I left you hanging

25:36.154 --> 25:37.387
with all those reporters.

25:37.422 --> 25:38.521
It was just, well...

25:38.557 --> 25:40.123
Don't make me relive it.

25:40.158 --> 25:41.736
Well, the good news is
we're back on our feet,

25:41.760 --> 25:43.059
and we're days away from having

25:43.094 --> 25:44.861
this whole trial business behind us.

25:44.896 --> 25:47.297
A white wine, please,
and for the lady...

25:47.332 --> 25:48.598
A white wine as well.

25:50.302 --> 25:53.369
Our lawyer, Bram Keller...
He thinks that this trial could

25:53.405 --> 25:54.804
be as important as Scopes.

25:54.840 --> 25:56.105
Didn't Scopes lose?

25:56.141 --> 25:58.408
He did. Yes. But we won't.

25:58.443 --> 26:01.544
And even if we do, Keller
assures us that any outcome

26:01.613 --> 26:02.812
works to our advantage.

26:02.848 --> 26:04.948
If we win, great. If we lose, we appeal.

26:04.983 --> 26:06.093
We become a cause celeb.

26:06.117 --> 26:08.251
- Hello, Arnold.
- Bob.

26:08.286 --> 26:11.454
Arnold, I'd like to introduce
you to Virginia Johnson,

26:11.490 --> 26:13.823
of Masters & Johnson.

26:13.859 --> 26:15.058
Arnold Ketterman.

26:15.093 --> 26:16.793
Arnold runs things around here.

26:16.828 --> 26:18.394
Oh, it's a real pleasure.

26:18.430 --> 26:21.264
Virginia and I go way back.

26:21.299 --> 26:22.799
Is that right?

26:24.436 --> 26:25.668
'Scuse me.

26:26.605 --> 26:28.471
What was that?

26:28.507 --> 26:30.073
What?

26:30.108 --> 26:33.009
Another white wine, pronto.

26:38.650 --> 26:40.817
I believe what we just did...

26:40.852 --> 26:43.953
violates section 1-1, subsection 010,

26:43.989 --> 26:46.089
of the Missouri criminal code.

26:49.194 --> 26:50.994
Don't worry. I won't
bring it up in court.

26:51.029 --> 26:53.663
In court?

26:53.698 --> 26:56.332
Keller's not gonna put
you on the stand, is he?

26:56.368 --> 26:59.502
Section 546, subsection 260,

26:59.538 --> 27:01.838
of the Missouri Revised Statutes:

27:01.873 --> 27:04.774
"a wife cannot be forced to
testify against her husband."

27:04.809 --> 27:06.175
How are you smoking that stuff

27:06.211 --> 27:08.311
and still managing to recite legal code?

27:08.346 --> 27:10.046
You tell me.

27:10.081 --> 27:12.482
- Here. Try it.
- No. I'm fine.

27:12.517 --> 27:14.884
Oh, come on, Bill.
You're a research scientist.

27:14.920 --> 27:16.653
Aren't you a little bit curious?

27:16.688 --> 27:18.621
All right. One puff.

27:18.657 --> 27:20.356
I believe they call it a hit.

27:22.661 --> 27:24.427
Do they?

27:28.533 --> 27:30.833
Oh!

27:32.404 --> 27:34.871
God, it smells like a wrestling mat.

27:36.207 --> 27:39.042
- Ohh... this bed is great.
- Mm.

27:39.077 --> 27:40.710
When did you get it?

27:40.745 --> 27:43.580
There was a Sears across the
street from the Salvation Army.

27:43.615 --> 27:47.016
I went there right after I
gave away all your clothes.

27:47.052 --> 27:48.551
The woman there didn't even blink,

27:48.587 --> 27:50.053
she'd seen it so many times.

27:50.088 --> 27:52.188
Well, you were right to do it.

27:52.223 --> 27:53.690
- The clothes?
- No, the bed.

27:53.725 --> 27:55.258
It's great.

27:55.293 --> 27:57.660
Whoo-hoo-hoo-hoo!

27:59.598 --> 28:01.664
Ah.

28:01.700 --> 28:04.100
So, come on. What else should
we have done differently, Lib?

28:04.135 --> 28:05.768
- Hon...
- Oh, the sex. I know.

28:05.804 --> 28:08.338
I know. But what else besides that?

28:08.373 --> 28:10.707
Come on, Bill. We're having a nice time.

28:10.742 --> 28:14.110
Let's not drudge up
the list of grievances.

28:14.145 --> 28:16.045
Well, now's your chance.

28:16.081 --> 28:18.648
I can't promise I'll always
be this open to hearing them.

28:19.718 --> 28:21.417
Fine. Fine.

28:22.420 --> 28:24.454
We should've had friends.

28:24.489 --> 28:26.522
- We had friends.
- No. Real friends.

28:26.558 --> 28:29.292
Not just Virginia.

28:29.327 --> 28:33.029
You know, other couples
and... and neighbors.

28:33.064 --> 28:36.933
We should've had dinner
parties and played music,

28:36.968 --> 28:38.601
played charades.

28:40.972 --> 28:43.306
Three words.

28:43.341 --> 28:45.975
First word.

28:46.011 --> 28:46.809
You.

28:46.845 --> 28:48.678
Mm. Second word.

28:51.282 --> 28:53.049
Sounds like.

28:53.084 --> 28:54.217
Eat.

28:54.252 --> 28:56.319
Sounds like "eat."

28:56.354 --> 28:57.887
Back. Eat back.

28:57.922 --> 28:58.955
Past tense.

28:58.990 --> 29:00.790
Ate. Sounds like "ate"!

29:00.825 --> 29:03.326
Rate. Mate. Hate.

29:03.361 --> 29:04.994
Hate. You hate...

29:05.030 --> 29:06.062
I hate charades.

29:08.633 --> 29:10.166
No, you're right. You're right.

29:10.201 --> 29:12.268
I should've tried harder
to meet new people.

29:13.972 --> 29:15.138
I never enjoyed it.

29:15.173 --> 29:17.306
I don't understand that.

29:17.342 --> 29:19.409
Well...

29:19.444 --> 29:22.912
I don't know, I...

29:22.947 --> 29:24.847
I'm always afraid people won't like me.

29:24.883 --> 29:26.582
- Why?
- Because...

29:26.618 --> 29:27.850
people don't like me.

29:30.455 --> 29:32.422
Oh, we should've had more fun.

29:32.457 --> 29:33.790
We should've travelled more.

29:33.825 --> 29:34.957
We travelled.

29:34.993 --> 29:37.660
Oh, not just to medical conventions.

29:37.696 --> 29:40.963
We should've taken the
kids to Disneyland.

29:40.999 --> 29:42.799
You wanted to go to Disneyland?

29:42.834 --> 29:44.200
Why didn't you say?

29:44.235 --> 29:48.638
Bill Masters on the spinning teacups?

29:48.673 --> 29:49.939
Isn't that what we just did?

29:49.974 --> 29:52.041
Mmm, I believe they also have a ride

29:52.077 --> 29:54.377
called the Carousel of Progress.

29:54.412 --> 29:56.345
- Progress?
- Mm.

29:56.381 --> 29:58.514
Sounds about right.

29:58.550 --> 30:00.383
You want to go around again?

30:04.155 --> 30:05.988
Mommy.

30:06.024 --> 30:08.658
Honey, did you have a bad dream?

30:08.693 --> 30:11.828
I'm so sorry. Let's go get you
a snack and tell a story.

30:13.198 --> 30:14.731
What was it? The monsters again?

30:14.766 --> 30:16.032
- Yeah.
- Aww.

30:16.067 --> 30:17.834
The whole novel is narrated

30:17.869 --> 30:19.402
by a guy who's being held captive

30:19.437 --> 30:21.003
on a planet called Tralfamadore.

30:21.039 --> 30:22.071
- Ah.
- He's on exhibit

30:22.107 --> 30:23.840
in some kind of alien zoo

